<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is included in total cost of car ownership?", answer: "Total cost of ownership includes the purchase price, sales tax, loan interest, insurance premiums, fuel costs, routine maintenance (oil changes, tires, brakes), repairs, registration and inspection fees, and depreciation. Many buyers focus only on the monthly payment but the true cost is typically 1.5 to 2 times the purchase price over a 5-year ownership period." },
  { question: "How much does car insurance typically cost?", answer: "Average annual car insurance in the US costs $1,500-$2,500 for full coverage, depending on your age, location, driving history, credit score, and vehicle type. Newer and more expensive vehicles cost more to insure. Young drivers under 25 pay significantly more. Liability-only coverage is cheaper at $500-$800 annually but provides less protection." },
  { question: "What are average car maintenance costs per year?", answer: "Average annual maintenance costs are roughly $500-$700 for a new vehicle under warranty, rising to $800-$1,200 for vehicles 5-10 years old. Luxury and European vehicles typically cost more to maintain at $1,000-$2,000 annually. These figures include oil changes, tire rotation, brake service, filters, and minor repairs but exclude major repairs like transmission or engine work." },
  { question: "How do I calculate my monthly fuel cost?", answer: "Divide your monthly driving miles by your vehicle's MPG to get gallons used, then multiply by the gas price. For example: 1,000 miles per month / 25 MPG = 40 gallons x $3.50 per gallon = $140 per month in fuel. The average American drives about 1,100 miles per month, spending $150-$200 on gasoline." },
  { question: "Is it cheaper to buy new or used?", answer: "Used cars are almost always cheaper in total cost of ownership. A 3-year-old vehicle has already lost 35-45% of its value to depreciation, has lower insurance premiums, and often lower registration fees. However, new cars come with full warranties, latest safety features, and better financing rates. The sweet spot for value is typically a 2-3 year old certified pre-owned vehicle." }
]) %>

